*****
[2] Zimbabwe (Harare)
Date: Sun 8 Apr 2012
Source: The Standard [edited]
http://allafrica.com/stories/printable/201204080222.html


Cases of typhoid are still being reported in Harare's high-density suburbs every day since the outbreak of the disease in October 2011. Head of Harare's 2 infectious disease hospitals, Beatrice and Wilkins, Clemence Duri said most of the cases were emanating from Dzivarasekwa and Kuwadzana high-density suburbs, areas which always experience frequent water cuts.

"As of [1 Jan 2012], we were receiving 90 cases per day in Dzivarasekwa and Kuwadzana which were the highest number of cases but now we are getting less than 20," Duri said. "Admissions are now very few compared to January [2012]. We have since adopted a preventive strategy because of the risk that it can spread to other areas."

More than 4000 cases of typhoid have been recorded in Harare since October 2011 while nearly 1000 people have been treated for dysentery in the past 2 months.

[Byline: Jennifer Dube]

